Rile NEWS -- user-visible changes.

Copyright (c) 2026 Robert Charusta <rch-public@posteo.net>
SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-3.0-or-later

* Noteworthy changes since release 0.9.0 (unreleased)

Interface features:

* Side-by-side split windows now reserve and draw a visible separator column so
  adjacent buffer text and mode lines no longer run together.

Editing features:

* `query-replace-regexp` is now available through `C-M-%` and `M-x`. It uses
  Rile's built-in line-local regexp subset with literal replacement text, keeps
  separate regexp prompt history, and rejects regexps that can match empty text.

* Query-replace search and replacement prompts now support in-session `M-p` and
  `M-n` history recall.


* Noteworthy changes in release 0.9.0 (2026-07-05)

This is the first public pre-1.0 Rile release.  Rile is a small,
terminal-native, UTF-8-capable Emacs-style editor written in Rust.

Editing features:

* Open existing UTF-8 files and create missing files from the terminal.
* Save through a same-directory temporary file and rename.  Existing file
  permissions are preserved across replacement, and stale temporary-name
  collisions are retried.  Use C-x s to offer to save each modified
  file-backed buffer.
* Keep save backups disabled by default.  When `backup_on_save = true`, Rile
  writes one persistent backup of the original file contents per buffer visit.
  Empty `backup_directory` uses sibling `file~` backups; otherwise path-based
  mapped backup names are written into the configured directory.
* Keep Emacs-style auto-save disabled by default.  When `auto_save = true`, Rile
  writes dirty file-visiting buffers to `#file#` auto-save files after the
  configured key-event interval or idle timeout.  Explicit saves delete
  current-session auto-save files by default, while preserving pre-existing
  recovery files; opening a file with a newer auto-save file warns so it can be
  opened manually for recovery.
* Insert printable UTF-8 text, tabs, and new lines.
* Move by character, line, visible page, repeated C-l center/top/bottom
  recentering, M-r middle/top/bottom window-line movement, beginning/end of
  line, indentation, word, paragraph, and sentence.  Common Ctrl-arrow,
  Ctrl-Home, and Ctrl-End terminal sequences are aliases for the matching word,
  paragraph, and buffer-boundary movement commands.
* Delete characters, kill words and lines, set a mark, mark the whole buffer,
  kill/copy regions, yank coalesced consecutive kills, and rotate yanks with
  M-y.
* Mark rectangular columns with C-x SPC; C-w and M-w kill or copy the rectangle,
  and regular C-y yanks rectangle entries as columns.  Use C-x r k, C-x r M-w,
  C-x r y, C-x r d, C-x r c, C-x r o, C-x r t, and C-x r N for explicit
  rectangle kill, copy, yank, delete, clear, open, string replacement, and line
  numbering operations without registers.
* Store point, text, rectangle, and number registers with C-x r SPC, C-x r s,
  C-x r r, and C-x r n; jump or insert them with C-x r j and C-x r i, and
  increment number registers with C-x r +.
* Supply repeat counts with C-u for repeatable movement, insertion, deletion,
  kill, and open-line commands.
* Record keyboard macros with C-x (, finish them with C-x ), and replay them
  with C-x e, including C-u repeat counts for macro execution.  F3 starts macro
  recording and F4 stops recording or replays the last macro on terminals that
  send common function-key escape sequences.
* Join the current line to the previous line with M-^.
* Convert word case with M-l, M-u, and M-c, and convert active-region case with
  C-x C-l and C-x C-u.
* Transpose characters around point with C-t, words with M-t, and lines with
  C-x C-t.
* Fill plain-text paragraphs with M-q, including active-region paragraph filling
  and a configurable fill column.
* Insert and toggle line comments with M-; in Rust, C, shell, and TOML buffers.
  Region line-comment commands are also available through M-x comment-region and
  M-x uncomment-region.
* Delete spaces and tabs around point with M-\\, or only before point with a
  prefix argument.  Delete redundant blank lines around point with C-x C-o, and
  remove trailing spaces and tabs with M-x delete-trailing-whitespace.
* Collapse whitespace around point with M-x just-one-space.
* Insert a newline with C-j through the newline-and-indent command.  In the
  current plain-text mode, point is left at the start of the new line.
* Quote the next key with C-q to insert printable text, Tab, or Enter
  literally.
* Search forward and backward with regular expressions using C-M-s and C-M-r.
  Rile's built-in line-local regexp subset supports `.`, `*`, `+`, `?`, `^`,
  `$`, escaped metacharacters, and character classes including ranges and
  negation.
* Recall accepted incremental-search strings with M-p and M-n.  Literal search
  and regexp search keep separate histories, and forward/backward search share
  history within each kind.
* Undo current-buffer edits with grouped normal typing.  Undoing back to the
  saved state clears the modified flag, and Emacs-style undo traversal can redo
  finalized undo sequences.  M-x undo-only and M-x undo-redo are available for
  explicit undo-family behavior.  Repeated undo and redo cycles can return to
  the original saved file state.  Undo, redo, and exhausted-undo live
  minibuffer messages use Emacs-style wording.
* Run commands through M-x with command-name completion.
* Run shell commands with M-!, display captured stdout/stderr by default, and
  insert stdout with C-u M-!.  Use M-| to send the active region to stdin and
  C-u M-| to replace the region with successful stdout.
* Open files through C-x C-f with file-name completion and a visible editable
  current-directory base.  Tab inserts the selected candidate, Enter accepts
  selected existing paths, directories descend after Tab, exact input, explicit
  selection, or a typed directory prefix, substring candidate matching works, and
  M-RET keeps raw missing-file input available.
* Insert file contents at point with C-x i and file-name completion, including
  selected existing-path acceptance on Enter.
* Open files read-only through C-x C-r with file-name completion, including
  selected existing-path acceptance on Enter.
* Revert file-backed buffers from disk with C-x C-v and clear a buffer's
  modified flag with M-x not-modified.  M-x auto-revert-mode and M-x
  global-auto-revert-mode reload externally changed clean file buffers while
  idle.
* Toggle normal buffers read-only and writable with C-x C-q.
* Switch buffers through C-x b with buffer-name completion, selected-candidate
  insertion on Tab, selected-candidate acceptance on Enter, default-buffer
  switching on empty input, and preserved point.
* List buffers through C-x C-b in a read-only *Buffer List* window.
* Kill buffers through C-x k with buffer-name completion, selected-candidate
  insertion on Tab, selected-candidate acceptance on Enter, and Emacs-style
  y-or-n-p dirty-buffer confirmation.
* Prompt before C-x C-c exits when normal buffers have unsaved changes.
* Suspend Rile with C-z / suspend-frame on terminals with job control, restoring
  terminal state before suspension and redrawing after resume.
* Report point location with C-x =.
* Describe key bindings with C-h k, interactive commands with C-h f,
  configuration options with C-h v, active modes with C-h m, and the current
  buffer with M-x describe-buffer.  Command and key help use prose-first,
  Emacs-like formatting while Rile-specific metadata remains explicit.
  Empty command and option prompts, including M-x, C-h f, and C-h v, accept the
  visible selected completion candidate on Enter; file prompts start from their
  visible current-directory base.
* Show version, build profile, feature-reporting status, terminal backend,
  config path, current directory, and diagnostic guidance with C-h C-a /
  about-rile.
* Review transient status and error history with C-h e in a read-only
  *Messages* buffer that updates while it is visible.
* Edit minibuffer prompt text with cursor movement using C-a/Home, C-e/End,
  C-f/Right, C-b/Left, M-f, and M-b.  C-d/Delete deletes after point; C-k, M-d,
  M-Backspace, and terminal-encoded C-Backspace kill prompt text into the normal
  kill ring.  Completion counters and prompt labels use minibuffer styling while
  editable prompt input stays in the default face.  Long prompts keep the
  cursor-side tail visible.
  Recall minibuffer prompt history with M-p and M-n, and page completion
  candidates with C-v/PageDown and M-v/PageUp.
* Completion matching no longer supports full regular-expression components.
  Orderless command, option, and buffer completion keeps literal components,
  smart case, `!foo` negation, `=foo` force-literal components, and simple
  literal anchors with `^foo`, `foo$`, and `^foo$`; other regexp metacharacters
  are matched as literal text.
* Keep the terminal cursor on active minibuffer prompts, including completion
  prompts, instead of leaving it at the editing buffer point.

Interface features:

* Start with a clean *Rile* welcome buffer when no file is given.
* Display Emacs-style mode lines with buffer state, position, and major
  mode.
* Inspect active major, syntax, minor, and special-buffer modes through a typed
  mode registry.
* Use blank unused rows instead of marker characters.
* Manage multiple buffers with C-x b, C-x C-b, and C-x k.
* Split, delete, and select windows with common Emacs key bindings.
* Scroll viewports automatically to keep point visible, including Emacs-style
  horizontal recentering on clipped long lines.
* Keep active-region highlighting visible on clipped long lines and selected
  line-end space.
* Use minibuffer prompts for commands, file names, buffers, search, and
  query replace.
* Complete M-x command names, C-h f command names, C-h v option names,
  C-x C-f/C-x C-r/C-x i file names, and C-x b/C-x k buffer names with the
  default vertical candidate list, optional *Completions* buffer fallback, or
  experimental ido-style inline display.  Tab inserts the selected candidate in
  completion prompts, Enter accepts it unless exact typed input is preserved,
  and M-RET submits raw minibuffer input.
  Command, option, and buffer matching defaults to modern orderless-style
  behavior: space-separated components must all match in any order, lowercase
  components match case-insensitively, simple literal anchors are accepted,
  `!foo` negates a component, and `=foo` forces literal matching.  File
  completion uses Emacs-style file-category prefix, word-component, and
  substring matching by default instead of orderless, with smart-case literal
  matching.  The configurable completion matching strategies are `orderless`,
  `prefix`, and `substring`; the earlier experimental `basic-substring` value
  has been removed before the first release.
  Command completions show the first known key binding when available.
* Complete C-h f command names with the shared command-completion source and
  C-h v option names with the option registry.
* Navigate command, file, buffer, write-file, goto-line, rectangle,
  shell-command, describe-function, describe-variable, and accepted
  incremental-search prompt history with M-p and M-n.

Search and replacement:

* Incremental forward and backward search with visible matches and explicit
  wrap-after-failure behavior.
* Search-history navigation with M-p and M-n during incremental search.  Search
  strings are recorded after accepting the search with Enter.
* Interactive query replace with y, n, !, q, Escape, and C-g choices.
* Literal incremental search and query replace are exact UTF-8 substring
  matching within individual lines.  Regexp incremental search uses Rile's
  built-in line-local regexp subset.  Query replace does not wrap around the
  buffer, and no search command matches across line breaks yet.

Display and configuration:

* Highlight Rust, C, shell, Markdown, and TOML using simple line-local
  highlighters.
* Select Emacs-style major-mode names from file extensions.
* Configure tab width, fill column, line numbers, syntax highlighting, search
  highlighting, theme, command-completion style, and optional save backups in
  ~/.config/rile/config.toml.
* Toggle line numbers, syntax highlighting, and search highlighting from
  M-x.
* Use either the default colored theme or a mostly monochrome theme.

Hardening and development:

* Reject invalid UTF-8 and NUL-containing binary files instead of opening
  them lossily.
* Optionally write sibling file~ backups before saving existing files.
* Provide deterministic `--visual-test` and `--test-size WIDTHxHEIGHT`
  developer flags for future PTY, snapshot, and VHS terminal testing.
* Provide optional Emacs reference-capture tooling alongside Zile and kg for
  base and modern Vertico/Marginalia terminal behavior evidence.
* Provide GPL-3.0-or-later licensing, clean-room reference notices,
  containerized development tooling, and a canonical make verify quality
  gate.
